Gene Expression data analysis of ETS2 mediated tumor suppressive function and MET oncogene inhibition in human non-small cell lung cancer

Yahya Al Sabeh

2024-01-16

Background

Researchers performed gene expression profiling using Human Gene 1.0 ST platform of 80 lung adenocarcinomas and 30 normal lung tissues to better understand the biology of this significant fraction of NSCLC. Overall design: Lung adenocarcinomas were comprised of never-smoker (n=40) and smoker (n=40) adenocarcinomas. Furthermore, (n=30) of the never-smoker cases normal lung tissue was provided as control. Gene expression profiling was performed on the samples to identify differentially expressed profiles between lung adenocarcinomas and normal lung tissues.

Statistical Analysis- 2-way Anova with 2 Levels

aov2.all.genes <- function(x,s1,s2, s3, s4) {
  x1 <- as.numeric(x[s1])
  x2 <- as.numeric(x[s2])
  y1 <- as.numeric(x[s3])
  y2 <- as.numeric(x[s4])
  fac <- c(rep('S-',length(x1)), rep('S+',length(x2)), rep('S-', 40), rep('S+',39), rep('S-',length(y2)))
  can <- c(rep('C+', 40), rep('C-', length(y2)), rep('C+', length(x2)),rep('C+', length(y1)),rep('C-', length(y2)))
  a.dat <- data.frame(as.factor(fac),as.factor(can), c(x1,x2,y1,y2))
  names(a.dat) <- c('smoke','cancer','express')
  p.out <- summary(aov(express~smoke+cancer, a.dat))[[1]][1:2,5]
  #p.out <- summary(aov(express~factor, a.dat))[[1]][1,4]   # use to get F-statistic
  return(as.numeric(p.out))
}
rawp <- apply(eset,1,aov2.all.genes,s1=colnames(eset[,1:69]),s2=colnames(eset[,70:108]),
              s3=c(colnames(eset[,1:40]),colnames(eset[,70:108])), s4=c(colnames(eset[,41:69])))
rownames(rawp)<-c('smoke','cancer')
